<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="81">
We provisionally retain this species in sect. 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Eremopoa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="81" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Pseudopoa">Pseudopoa</taxonomicName>
, despite its divergent phylogenetic placement. The species is morphologically similar to other members of the section. As noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mill, RR" journalOrPublisher="Opera Biologica" pageId="22" pageNumber="91" refId="B39" refString="Mill, RR, 1985. Eremopoa, Nephelochloa, Catabrosella, Colpodium, Hyalopoa, Catabrosa, Paracolpodium. In: Davis PH (Ed.) Flora of Turkey and East Aegean Islands, Vol. 9. Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh, 486-501." title="Eremopoa, Nephelochloa, Catabrosella, Colpodium, Hyalopoa, Catabrosa, Paracolpodium. In: Davis PH (Ed.) Flora of Turkey and East Aegean Islands, Vol. 9. Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh, 486 - 501." year="1985">Mill (1985)</bibRefCitation>
, it is most like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soreng, Cabi &amp; L. J. Gillespie" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Soreng, Cabi &amp; L. J. Gillespie" baseAuthorityYear="2018" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa nephelochloides" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="81" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nephelochloides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="81">Poa nephelochloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Roshev., but the anthers are smaller. Some populations of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. millii" pageId="12" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="millii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="81">P. millii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
approach 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. attalica" pageId="12" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="attalica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="81">P. attalica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and are problematical to separate (see under 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. millii" pageId="12" pageNumber="81" rank="species" species="millii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="81">P. millii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Further molecular study is needed to determine if the three species are closely related and if a new section is warranted.
</paragraph>
